  "prompt": "Why is coal not considered a mineral?",
  "response": "Coal is not considered a mineral because it does not meet all the standard geological criteria for a mineral. Here are the specific reasons:\n\n1. Origin: Coal is an organic sedimentary rock formed from the decomposition of plant materials over millions of years, whereas minerals are inorganic substances.\n\n2. Composition: Minerals have a definite chemical composition and crystal structure. Coal's composition is variable and lacks a fixed chemical formula.\n\n3. Crystal structure: Minerals have a regular, repeating atomic arrangement. Coal does not have a consistent crystal structure.\n\n4. Natural formation: Minerals are formed through geological processes, while coal is primarily a biological product created from the accumulation and transformation of plant matter.\n\n5. Consistency: Minerals typically have consistent physical properties like hardness and specific gravity. Coal's properties can vary widely depending on its stage of formation and organic material.\n\nAlthough coal is not technically a mineral, it is still an important geological resource used for energy production. Geologists classify coal as an organic sedimentary rock rather than a mineral.",
